<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-643-634  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 643 634.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  July 16 1990 v24 n29 p54(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Telecom users root against underdogs: as power of ATandamp;T slips,users call for controls on increasingly powerful Sprint, MCI.andO;(Analysis)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A user survey indicates that major telecommunications users arefavoring the deregulation of AT and T while beginning to favorrestrictions on the operations of its major competitors.andP;  Thechange in attitude towards MCI Communications and US Sprintindicates that the playing field has become more even in the $50billion market.andP;  Recently, the FCC has indicated that there may bea phase-out of government regulations restricting the operationsof AT and T. As the market shares of MCI and US Sprint haveincreased, the pressure for reduced regulation of AT and T hasincreased.andP;  Some users favor a system in which all long distancecarriers would post public notices of customer voice and dataservices.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (marketing)MCI Communications Corp. (marketing)US Sprint Communications Co. (marketing).andO;Ticker:    T; MCIC.andO;Topic:     Telephone CompaniesMarket AnalysisCompetitionUser StudiesGovernment RegulationUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionTelecommunications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>